div.head:
NPNF1-09. St. Chrysostom: On the Priesthood;
Ascetic Treatises; Select Homilies and Letters;
Homilies on the Statutes

div.p:
The work on the Priesthood was translated by Hollier (London, 1728); Bunce (London,
1759); Hohler (Cambridge, 1837); Marsh (London, 1844); Harris Cowper (London, 1866);
and Stephens (N. York, 1888, prepared for this “Library”).

Chrysostom attracted large audiences, and among them many who would rather have
gone to the theatre than hear any ordinary preacher. He held them spell-bound to the close.
Sometimes they manifested their admiration by noisy applause, and when he rebuked them
for it, they would applaud his rebuke. “You praise,” he would tell them, “what I have said,
and receive my exhortation with tumults of applause; but show your approbation by obedience;
that is the only praise I seek.”

